description.text:
Just playing with Fusion 360 learning a few tricks and tips from videos.. mades this ball thing as a cat toy ...

actually designed to NOT roll smoothly so the cat reacts to it better than just a ball that rolls.

This is my Stratux case.

My goals in designing this case were:

  • Compact, short
  • No support needed
  • Folding antennas that do NOT rotate around the mounting axis.
  • Label the top cover to make it easier to remember which antenna goes where (978Mhz and 1090Mhz).
  • Make it stronger than it hopefully needs to be. I did this so that it would resist warping due to a hot cockpit.

All previous cases that have I used have always required you to rotate the antenna on the same axis that you mount the antenna. This always led to the antenna mount becoming lose and unscrew. It also twisted the internal antenna wire.

My design allows you to fold the antenna using the antenna's elbow, not rotation. It also makes it very compact and easy to slip in to your flight bag without snagging.

I filleted the internal screw mounts to resist snapping from the torque of installing screws.

It's designed to use:
2.5mm x 8mm (6 screws for top)
2.5mm x 4mm (4 screws to mount Raspberry Pi)

The screws I used are "laptop" screws from Amazon.

If the screws are loose, (maybe you have your printer extrusion multiplier lower than mine), try 3.0mm screws instead of 2.5mm.

description.text:
Cricut Cutting Blade Attachment for the Makergear M2

First the Disclaimer........

This is a work in progress (I am uploading this per request.)

This attachment is NOT for the average user. It requires advanced knowledge of the M2 printer such as moving and calibrating your Z-stop. It also requires advanced g-code editing and slicer setting to make work...

If you are not an advanced printer user and don't know what your doing please do not try to use this... I make no guarantees or warranties as to the accuracy or completeness of, or results to be obtained from accessing and using the Information herein.

With all that being said........

Hardware Required
(2) 8/32" x 3/4" Flat Head Screws
(2) 8/32" Nuts
(1) 6/32" x 7/8" Socket Head Screw
(2) 6/32" x 1/2" Socket Head Screws
(3) 6/32" Heat Set Inserts
Cricut 2001401 Deep Cut Blade and Housing
Cricut 2001974 Adhesive Cutting Mat

For use on the Makergear M2 with V4 hotend. The Filamet Drive and Hot end are removed and printed blade attachment mounts to the V4 mount with the listed hardware.

The blade holder has a certain amount of cutting depth adjustment that can be made by turning the top dial but your z-stop height my need to be changed to use this attachment. The adhesive mat (not shown) is clipped to the bed and the paper sticks right to it. For best results you need to use a thick craft type paper. Regular printer paper (even the thick stuff) will likely just tear instead of being cut.

You'll have to figure out the correct setting for your printer/software (Some features to the start up script need to be removed such as the initial wipe feature, ect.) but other important basics I use are....

Top and Bottom Layers = 0
Outline/Perimeter Shells = 1
Retraction Vertical Lift = 1-2 mm (very important so the blade lifts when crossing open areas.)

No skirts or brims.
You only what to run one print/cutting layer so I set my layer height to .10 mm and the stop printing feature (advanced tab) also to .10mm.

Printing/cutting speed will have to be figured out for your paper type I think I used 2000 mm/min with the first layer set to 50% so it's actually probably 1000 mm/min.

I've used this to make some lettering for signs from vinyl and it works great. It's a little tricky getting the z-height correct so it just cuts through the vinyl and not the backing and you have to have a perfect bed level but it works great once thats all set.

AGAIN - I make no guarantees or warranties as to the accuracy or completeness of, or results to be obtained from accessing and using the Information herein.

USE AT YOUR OWN RISK.

I added some thermal IR pictures demonstrating how heatsinks on the NEMA motors work very well. The MDF lower build plate support does well as an insulator. The aluminum plate under the mirror does a good job of evenly distributing the heat from the Kapton heating element.

M3 screws are used to assemble the effector, attach the hall effect endstops, bolt the carriages to the linear rail carriages, attached NEMA motors, and bolt the linear rails to the aluminum extrusions. M5 screws are used to bolt aluminum extrusions to printed vertices, hold the plate holders in place, and attach extruder to the aluminum frame.

My wife is a huge NASCAR fan and of course, her favorite driver is Dale Earnhardt Junior. Wanting to print her something NASCAR related, I searched Thingiverse and came across this 88 logo with stand. I decided to modify it to remove the stand (it stands nicely on it's own) and adjust it for multi-color printing (with a single extruder printer).

Simply print the base (black) and leave it affixed to your heat bed. Load the color for the face (white), zero your Z axis to the top the of base and then load and slice the face. You may need to adjust your start code and/or edit your gcode after slicing to persuade your printer not to rezero the Z axis at the start of the print. You can also leave the heat bed disabled. Print and then repeat for the accent (red).

It is easily scaled (just be sure to center each piece on the heat bed so they stack properly), about 10 cm wide at 100%.

I hope my wife likes it!

description.text:
Have one of those Chinese laser engravers that are so plentiful that you want to repurpose? I needed to automate some measurements for research and found that it is cheaper to buy one of these than it is to purchase the materials for or buy a dedicated XY gantry.

To repurpose it requires some kind of mount to replace the included laser with my waveguide. Modularity would be nice.

As a frequent user of firearms/competition shooter, I thought:

  • What holds cylindrical objects in place under recoil? Scope rings.
  • What is superior in both precision and recoil mitigation to scope rings if you have the cash? One piece mount.
  • What is our favorite (assuming weight isn't a huge factor) modular mounting system? PICATINNY RAILS!!!!

So I applied those concepts here, and the results are amazing compared to my last automated rig.

It's also standardized. Engineers love standards! (M1913, but this is NATO spec, not sure if there is a difference)

..AND I got paid to design the best, fully-parametric picatinny rail and clamp I've ever made!

The first attempt bolted onto the 4 holes in the original acryllic piece where the laser mounted. After designing/printing, I realized the holes in the laser engraver weren't square. Figures as much, crap QC. So I made a replacement for the entire piece. Uses same screws as what comes on the machine. Also included intermediate version without the nut retainers in case they change what nuts are used. Mine were M5 hardware.

Use to attach an unused flashlight for precision lighting of your sample! Or a housing for a different laser? Or a red dot scope for rapid defect acquisition inside your sample Or even this telescopic sight on a Burris one piece mount for superior view of distant samples. Duh. Lolololo

I guess you could also put a waveguide mount on it for detecting defects in composites with microwaves. I'm pretty exited to see what this thing can do with 2D capabilities.

description.text:
This vertical bubble machine blows bubbles not horizontally, but upwards. I needed this for a project: a witch cauldron from which bubbles emerge, glowing in the dark by having UV-A LEDs at the edge of the cauldron and using a UV bubble fluid.

Normal bubble machines have to blow bubbles in a horizontal or nearly horizontal direction, because the bubble wheel has to be oriented horizontally, with the lower part in a tank of bubble fluid. I had different ideas to overcome this problem, and in the end took a "ferris wheel" like approach.

For building this, you'll need a small 5V geared motor and a 12V pc fan (I used a rather strong one and ran it on the same 5V as the geared motor that's turning the wheel). Just place the bubble machine into a tray containing the bubble fluid.

You'll find detailled instructions to building this in my "Magic Cauldron" instructable here: http://www.instructables.com/id/Magic-Cauldron-Blowing-Glowing-Bubbles/. See for yourself which of the connecting bubble wands you want to print -- just print eight of them and mix them as you like. For my magic cauldron I used smaller ones, but when using just the bubble machine my kid's love the bigger ones very much.

Here's a video of the Vertical Bubble Machine in action: https://youtu.be/LEh5ZPtCJjE
Here's a video of the "Magic Cauldron", for which it was built: https://youtu.be/U5E8Jiy0ujM

And here you can see an interactive rendering of the machine to better understand how it fits together: http://a360.co/2aNOUte

I Decided to extend the Z axis on my Wanhao i3 printer as it was wanting to print some rather tall teardrop lampshades.

The whole process is very simple and only requires about $40 worth of parts, you will need:

  • 1.5 meters of 60 x 3mm equal mill aluminium angle. This can be found pretty readily at window manufacturers and good hardware stores.

  • Two T8 8mm screw length 500mm picth 2mm lead 8mm trapezoidal screw with 1pcs brass copper nut

http://www.aliexpress.com/item/T8-8mm-screw-length-500mm-picth-2mm-lead-8mm-trapezoidal-screw-with-brass-copper-nut-T8/32695471104.html?spm=2114.01010208.3.50.4sfxjz&ws_ab_test=searchweb201556_8,searchweb201602_5_10057_10056_10055_10037_10049_10059_10032_10058_10017_10060_10061_10062_10063_412,searchweb201603_1&btsid=0ba87918-6766-4968-ba09-ad2caf842c50

  • Two 8mm L600mm linear shaft OD 8mm x 600mm Cylinder Liner Rail Linear Shaft Optical Axis cnc parts

http://www.aliexpress.com/item/New-8mm-L600mm-linear-shaft-OD-8mm-x-600mm-Cylinder-Liner-Rail-Linear-Shaft-Optical-Axis/32355714675.html?spm=2114.13010608.0.58.IAWctS

  • You will also need a about 30 M3 x 8mm socket head screws

  • A 2.5mm drill and an M3 tap (or if you can't justify buying a tap just drill the holes out and use nuts from behind)*

  • A 1.6mm (or 1.5mm if you ream the hole slightly) drill and an M2 tap*

The original cable chains are enclosed and require the wire be fed through them which would mean removing the connectors from the end of the wires.
So I designed some open top extensions to fit into the original Z axis cable chain, this negates the need to disassemble the loom connectors. I fitted one of the open topped extensions between each original so that there was no chance of the cables popping out, you will need 20 of these.

A second Z axis chain for the opposite side will also need to be printed, but this one can be enclosed as it is easy to remove the connector and feed the wire through. You will need to print 40 of these, a bottom mount and the stepper motor mount.

The manufacturing process is very simple and mostly requires cutting, measuring and drilling the aluminium angle.

The first step is to measure your original feed-screw against the new longer feed screw. The difference in length between the two will determine how much longer than the originals to cut your aluminium angle. Simply add this difference in length to the length of your original steel uprights and cut the aluminium as squarely and consistently as you can.

Once you have two identically sized pieces of aluminium angle it's time to drill holes. The easiest way is to make cardboard templates of the screw locations from the inside of your original uprights. It's important to make and use the templates from the inside of the angle uprights in order to get an accurate measurement.

To get the elongated screw holes simply drill two 3mm holes side by side and angle the drill to join the two and clean away the waste.

Measure up from the bottom to drill the Z-axis support holes, being sure to use the 2.5mm drill then cutting a thread by running the M3 tap through them. The Z axis brace holes will need to be drilled at the same height as the top of the old upright holes.

The final drilling and tapping is for the Z-axis limit switch, simply make a template and measure up from the bottom, then drill the hole with the 1.5 or 1.6 mm drill and cut a thread with the M2 tap.

It's now simply a matter of cutting the bearing rods and reassembling the printer in the same way that you disassembled it. To cut the rod, measure your old bearing rod agains your old feed screw. You then add this distance to the length of your new feed screw and use this to mark and cut your new bearing rod.

To get the printer to recognise the extra length it's as simple as going into Repetier and changing the EEPROM values.

After doing this I realised that it would be a piece of cake to give the heater bed cable the same treatment as it was infuriatingly cumbersome and easily snagged. I simply printed another 22 closed cable chain pieces, designed a bottom bracket that clamps onto the steel frame, and a top bracket that mounts to the bottom of the build plate carrier so as to keep things well clear of the heat.

The bottom bracket slides over the frame and is held in place with two M3 bolts a which tighten into captive M3 nuts. If you have trouble getting the nuts into groove, heating them with a hot soldering iron will do the trick.

The top bracket just bolts through the carrier plate using M4 bolts into captive nuts at the bottom of the bracket, again a little heat with the soldering iron helps guide and lock the captive nuts in place. Then just thread your cable through the chain and wire things back the way they were. I'm using a 20x30mm build plate, but this cable chain should work just as well on the 20x20mm beds, it just might require a few less links, so experiment before bolting things into place.

REMEMBER! when printing the cable links make sure that you get your orientation right, you want the lobes at the end of the chains to face upward, otherwise the chain will overextend back onto itself!

Have fun!

description.text:
If you have an aero frame bike you would probably have found it challenging getting lights etc. to stay put on the seat post.

I designed this adapter to firmly secure my rear light and a MTB rear mudguard.

It converts the 5mm radius thin end of the post to a 22mm diameter. This prevents my attachments from pivoting to the side - not such a problem with my moon taillight, but essential to the mudguard.

I designed it to be printed in vase mode, as this produces a very light and strong piece with an excellent finish, however it can be sliced in the usual way if you wish.

When printing in vase mode it is desirable that the open end be secured, or it can twist and collapse. For this reason I have included an end cap which should be superglued to the open end of the adapter. For maximum strength squeeze a few drops of superglue down into the cavity before you glue the end on.

There are several versions included, a short (25mm) and long (37mm) version, and also a 25mm version which includes a strengthening flange that should remove the need to fit an end cap. This version is useful if your attachment must sit right against the seat post.

Parts are:

  • SeatPostAdapterBtm3.stl - End Cap for hollow printed adapters
  • SeatPostAdapterV4.1.stl - Strengthened 25mm seat post adapter
  • SeatPostAdapterV3.1.stl - Hollow 25mm seat post adapter
  • SeatPostAdapterLong.1.stl - Hollow 37mm seat post adapter

Note - these are hollow only when printed in vase mode - otherwise they are solid.

If using vase mode, please use 0.2mm layers, and specify 6 bottom layers for all parts.

READ UPDATES BELOW!!!
If you don't like reading, then read this: download the 2 files ending with v1.2. You don't need to download all files. This was designed from scratch and inspired by the "Yin Yang cable spool". The dimensions vary slightly (slightly larger). The design is significantly sturdier with thicker walls, floor and ceiling, but not to the point where it uses too much plastic or takes too long to print (takes me about 1hr 30min). Best of all, the tongue and groove mesh together perfectly and it operates surprisingly smoothly with minimal friction, but just enough to prevent it from popping out except by force. I'm able to spin both parts independently using only one hand. At the moment it works best with 3mm (v1.0 & v1.1) cables but you should be able to squeeze 4mm cables tightly. UPDATE 1 (v1.1): Slight modification made to lid and base, making it supremely easy to spin the lid within the base, and unspool the cable easily by holding both ends of the cable and pulling. Download v1.1. Version 1 still works well especially for thick cables that are less flexible. UPDATE 2 (v1.2): Modified the top part of the base slightly to make it 100% stronger as it tends to be more brittle due to the groove. Also increased support for 4mm cables, and made some minor modifications to the design to optimize printing. Download v1.2.

I wouldn't call my self a penny-pincher, but I just hate to waste money and resources on things without a (very good) reason. One of my problems is not having the patience to get the last drops of tomato ketchup out of the bottle.

Therefore I have made this sleeve/funnel to connect two bottles. This way I can just connect the bottles, leave them in the fridge and in about a day, the content of the top bottle will have run into the lower bottle.

I don't know if there is an international ketchup bottle standard that dictates the size of the bottle caps, but this sleeve fitted on the stokes (my preferred ketchup brand) bottles, the squeezy-bottles we have bought in out local hardware store and two other kinds of dressing and BBQ sauce we had in the fridge. The inner size of the sleeve is 36 mm and the thread has 4 mm pitch.

The sleeve is designed so that the sleeve it self does not come in direct contact with the ketchup, since the two bottles touch when they are connected.

I cleaned up the print with a hobby knife, 320 grit sandpaper and a mini file. I added a single coat of primer and a single coat of paint. Total time in post 30-45 min max on all three that I printed.

Hardware sizing and planning 
 Because the hardware that I am implementing from the tripod mounts is a simple cylinder, I started by making a cylinder to match the diameter and depth of the part in Blender.  I added a second cylinder object with the dimensions of the first plus the thickness of 4 perimeters from my printer.  My printer prints the outside perimeter at .55mm width so it will actually be 2.20mm wall thickness.  After that I make one loop cut in center, turn on smooth proportional editing, grab the bottom edge periment and scale it on the X,Y axis a predetermined diameter. After this I turn off proportional editing, grad the loop cut in the center and bevel it to make the base aesthetically pleasing.  Feel free to leave any questions in the comment section.

So it's Maker Faire season again here in Shenzhen and I wanted something to follow up last years DIY Hikaru Skirt (http://imgur.com/a/cAyO2). This time I wanted to try to come up with something completely original (at least as far as I know). While there are lots of 3D printed clothes in the news, nearly all are printed on expensive SLS printers and the source code is almost never published. Like all my projects, I wanted it to be Open Source and a realistic project for any Maker to build and improve on.

So I came up with this, a wearable array of LED lit infinity mirror tiles inspired by traditional Chinese 两当铠 armor.

The tiles form a flexible matrix that can be reconfigured into different garments, or even a bag. Every tile measures 66mm on each edge, and has four magnetic electrical conductors that can link it to it's neighboring tile. So long as each row and column gets power, there is endless variations that can be tried. With an Arduino and LED matrix controller, each individual tile can be controlled so complex patterns can play across the surface. This is just a first prototype though so all the lights get power continuously and there is no matrix control. There is room in the battery pack to add a Arduino later though.

I'll have a full parts list and printing instructions up within the next day, in the mean time you can get a pretty good idea of how it works here: http://imgur.com/a/N8MZd see it in action here: http://imgur.com/a/2sVBk and watch the video to see how to build your own below.

title: Mendel Y Foot For Deposition Bed

description.text:
Four of these feet will support a Mendel deposition bed. The semi-circular recess rests on the Y rails, so no bearings are required. The bed can be levelled by tightening the 2 Nylok nuts on each foot, thus compressing the spring structure.
The heads of the two M4x40 machine screws are recessed into the attachment bracket, and three small holes are provided. These nicely take No.4 3/8" to 1/2" countersunk or pan-head woodscrews - the SCAD file has an option for it.  The M4 screws are held captive by two nuts which are recessed, so no washers needed there.
This allows just one layer of bed to provide an adjustable flat upper surface for deposition.

Works best in PLA as this gives low friction. Washers are needed under the Nylok nuts. Two ordinary nuts may be locked off on one another in place of each Nylok. The same feet will happily run on 1/4" steel piano or music wire with no modification other than a little lubrication. Full assembly details for the Y-Bed are here: http://reprap.org/wiki/Y_Bed_Simplified

description.text:
Remix of Tom Sanlanderers fantastic extruder designed to mount on 2020 extrusion.
https://www.youmagine.com/designs/wip-cerbrisreborn-1-75mm-bowden-extruder

If you haven't seen his 3D printing YouTube series, have a look and maybe drop him a dollar in patreon for his efforts

Changes made are,
-reduced the free space around the hob to make it more flexy filament friendly, and
-reduced the bowden coupling location to one suitable for an M5 thread

Update 27/2/2017

  • added V4 body and clamp, this allows you to get around having to tap the hole or use acetone to shape it for the bowden coupling. All you need to do is print the V4 body and clamp, and the lever. The clamp holds the bowden coupling in place using M3 screw/nut

flashforge creator pro

No

0.2

80%

description.text:
21 January 2017 Update
This update adds an optional Base that incorporates a Cable Chain Mount Bracket. Printer side Cable Chain Bracket and Cable Chain Link files are located here:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2050826

https://youtu.be/Aoob5m4544s

Also introduced in this version is the addition of a 4mm boss on the upper surface around the PTFE Tube Connector along with increasing the connector hole to 9mm to accommodate a new 10mm threaded PTFE Tube Connector. This new connector allows the PTFE tube to pass through the itself and into the Filament Present Switch housing. This eliminates filament jamming during loading in cases where the filament has a small bend or the end is not chamfered. The PTFE Connector hole must be reamed and tapped to 10mm threads.

19 December 2016 Update
As noted below the indicated temperature on the front panel is about 10°C higher than programmed via either XYZware or Simplify 3D. This was observed even though the original XYZprinting Heater and Thermistor was retained.

Numerous posts on multiple blogs have noted a different Resistance vs Temperature curve between the stock thermistor and the one supplied by E3D V6 kit. With that in mind I ran a number of tests using a low cost contact Thermal Couple Meter. The test conditions:

  • Insert Thermal Couple into the heater pinch slot.
  • Run Head Clean Procedure
  • Monitor Test Set Temperature vs Front Panel Temp
  • Note Differences

Generally temperatures tracked within 10°C from room temperature to 200°C. At 200°C the front panel stops reporting temperature but the temp continues to be reported on S3D Control Panel. Observed temperatures are the average of the high and low values for each temperature range. The Test Set indicated temperature averaged 15°C less that the Front Panel and S3D values.

I ran a Calibration Cube Test changing the temperature every 10 layers in the following increments (255, 245, 235, 230, 225, 220). Adjusting for the above indication error I found the actual vs programmed temperatures varied less the 4°C. See spreadsheet in the files selection for actual values.

Conclusion
The supplied E3D V6 capsule is functionally equivalent to the stock terminator when installed with the E3D V6 hot end. Printer reported temperatures will be between 10-15°C higher that actual nozzle temperature.

NOTE
The test set is had an accuracy of +- 2.5°C

16 August 2016

These parts adapt a E3DV6 Hot End to a XYZprinting DaVinci 1.0 Pro printer Carriage. Installation of this adapter requires:

  • Removal of the 3 Snap-In mount screws and the mount,
  • Transfer for the stock Thermistor, Heater, Fan, and Circuit Board to the new Adapter

I have included pictures showing the existing mount screws and the screw details for the new mount.

Note: The new Adapter uses the outboard screw holes rather than the middle and right hand set.

The advantages of this adapter over others are:

  • Optimized Bowden Tube routing allowing for streight path from the tube to the Hot End virtually eliminating Feed Roller slippage for any filiment that can be printed at 250°C or less,
  • Bowden Tube no longer touches upper printer cover,
  • Maintains Nozzle height of the stock Hot End eliminating major Bed adjustment and leveling,
  • Increases Nozzle temperature 10°C to 250°C.

Printer:

XYZprinting Davinci 1.0 Pro

Rafts:

0.2mm

25%

Notes:

Only the Adapter Base requires supports. The Heat Sink Clamp Should be printed with the flat side down and may require supports for the recessed hex nut cavities depending on printer and material.

I recommend ABS or PETG (if your Printer can handle) for durability and heat resistance.

Direct Replacement of Drop-In Frame - No modifications required to Carriage

These parts adapt a genuine 1.75mm E3DV6 Hot End assembly to the XYZprinting DaVinci 1.0 Pro printer replacing the stock Drop-In mount. Other hot ends will probable work if they are geometrically identical to the E3D version.

The existing mount is removed by removing 3 screws that hold the stock mount to the Carriage and installing the Adapter printed from the files included herein. No modification to the Carriage is required.

The original configuration can be restored by simply reinstalling the DaVinci Drop-In Mount Flange using the 3 M3 Screws provided. This takes less than 5 minutes and requires only a T10 torx drive. See mount picture below:

Stock Drop-In Mount Design Features

The Adapter lowers the Filament Bowden Feed Tube enough that the tube no longer hits the printer cover. It also eliminates the extra PTFE tube and Funnel that was required for the Drop-In cartridge to function properly.

All hardware is firmly held in place with fasteners insuring optimal alignment of filament path resulting in negligible filament drag during operation. Filament slippage in the Feed Roller is virtually eliminated.

Finally the design positions the Nozzle at the same height as the stock Hot End Nozzle. This greatly reduces the Z-Axis adjustments required with some other designs.

You will need the following items in addition to the parts to be printed herein:
  • 1ea 10mm Male Thread 4mm Push In Joint Pneumatic Connectorhttps:
    (www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01IB81IHG)
  • 2ea M3x6 Screws - Top Adapter to Carriage (See Picture),
    (www.amazon.com/Alloy-Steel-Socket-Screws-Black/dp/B00W8YSCIS)
  • 2ea M3x10 Screws - Circuit Board to Adapter Base,
    (www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00W97A674)
  • 2ea M3x12 Screws - Bottom Adapter to Carriage (See Picture),
    (www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0143GZIHQ)
  • 4ea M3x20 Screws - Adapter Base to Hot End Clamp,
    (www.amazon.com/uxcell%C2%AE-M3x20mm-Socket-Screws-100Pcs/dp/B0143GZHDG)
  • 10ea M3x0.5mm Zinc Plated Nylon Insert Hex Lock Nuts Black
    (www.amazon.com/gp/product/B015A3DT2W)
  • 10ea M3 Stainless Steel Flat Washer, Black Oxide Finish, Meets DIN 125, M3 Hole Size, 3.2mm ID, 7mm OD, 0.5mm Nominal Thickness
    (www.amazon.com/gp/product/B009OK22RG)
  • 2ea Shroud to Clamp Screws - Steel Thread Rolling Screw for Plastic, Black Oxide Finish, Pan Head, Phillips Drive, #4-20 Thread Size, 1/2" Length
    (www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00GDYDS9W)
  • 4ea Fan to Shroud Steel - Thread Rolling Screw for Plastic, Black Oxide Finish, Pan Head, Star Drive, #4-20 Thread Size, 1" Length
    (www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00GDYYSBY)

Print the following 3 items from Thingiverse:
  • Adapter Base
  • Heat Sink Clamp
  • Fan Shroud
Assemble E3D V6 Hot End

Assemble E3DV6 Hot End using instructions supplied with the E3D Kit using existing Thermistor and Heater from stock Hot End. Optionally the capsul heater from the E3d Kit may be used but some temperature adjustment will be required at print time. See above Discussion inder Summary.

Flare the end of the PTFE tube that protrudes from the Heat Sink in order to create a larger target for the filament during loading. A counter sink tool or a #30 drill bit can be used to flare the tube end. Be sure no residue remains in the tube as the tube material will not melt at normal operating temperatures and will plug the nozzle.

Ream Screw Holes

Ream all screw holes except the 2 holes in the Heat Sink Clamp which are used to secure the Fan Shroud to the Heat Sink Clamp. Use a 3.5mm or #30 drill bit. M3 screws should fit smoothly into the holes without any slop. See Detail in image above.

Trim Thermistor Leads

Trim excessive Circuit Board Thermistor Connector lead length from the underside of the circuit board. Ideally the remaining lead and solder blob will not exceed 0.5mm. These leads could interfere with the top left Adapter Base fastener holding the Adapter Base to the Carriage. See Picture.

Apply Insulating Tape to Circuit Board Back Side

Apply Kapton or equivalent tape to the bottom of the circuit board to insulate the circuits from inadvertent contact with Adapter Base mounting screws,

Install Locknuts into Hex Cavities

Install 10ea Locknuts in the cavities provided in the Adapter Base and Heat Sink Clamp. The cavities are designed to hold the nuts firmly in place to ease screw installation. The best technique to seating the nuts is to start a nut on a M3 screw that is inserted into the respective hole and gently tap the nut into the cavity using the screw to center the nut. Be sure to align the nut and cavity geometry. Tighten the screw until the nut has bottomed out in the cavity, then remove the screw.

Install Washers into Recessed Screw Holes

Insert washers into the 4 recessed screw holes in the bottom of Adapter Base. Tap each washer into the recessed screw holes using a 5mm punch. Make sure the washer has bottomed out.

Install PTFE Tube Connector

Tap the hole at the top of the Adapter Base using a 10MM tap and corresponding drill bit.

Finger tighten the PTFE Connector until it bottoms out against the top of the Base. Do Not Over Tighten as the threads in the Adapter Base are easily stripped depending on material.

Test Mount Adapter Base onto Carriage

Mount the Adapter Base onto the Carriage using M3x6 Screws (top two holes) and M3x12 screws (bottom two Holes). Insure the top screws do not extend into the area the Circuit Board will occupy. There should be at least 2mm clearance between the screw and the bottom of the Circuit Board.

The Circuit Board will bottom out against two pads near the nut cavities. Use these pads as reference for screw clearance.

Remove the Adapter Base from the Carriage.

Install Circuit Board

Install Circuit Board from the stock Hot-End using 2 M3x10 Screws. Tighten finger tight pending installation of the E3DV6 assembly.

Install E3D v6 assembly into Adapter

Position E3DV6 Hot End onto Adapter Base. Do not use force. The Head Sink should fit into the groves freely. If not, check for foreign materials or over extrusion that has narrowed the mating surfaces. Position the Heater and Thermistor wires as indicated in the detail picture above.

Position the Heat Sink Clamp over the E3DV6 assembly. The Clamp should come to within 1mm of the Base. If not, inspect and remove any debris from the Clamp. Fasten the Clamp using 4 M3x20 screws. Tighten each screw until it begins to draw down the clamp then torque each screw 1/2 turn in a cross sequence until you can no longer rotate the E3DV6 Heat Sink, then tighten each screw 1/2 turn more. Inspect the clamp edges for equal distance between the Adapter Base and the Heat Sink Clamp and adjust screws as necessary to even out the Base to Clamp separation.

Align Filament Path

The filament should pass through the PTFE Connector, through the Filament Present switch into the PTFE Tube assembled into the Heat Sink during the E3DV6 buildup. If any misalignment is noted, loosen the screws holding the Circuit Board in place and adjust its position. Retighten screws after alignment.

Note: See the pictures below indicating proper alignment of the filament Bowden tube connector, Filament Present Switch, and Heat Sink PTFE tube.

Filament Path Alignment & Base Mount Nut Detail Install Fan Shroud

Attach Fan Shroud to Heat Sink Clamp using 2ea #4-20 Steel Rolling Thread Screw for Plastic - 1/2" in length.

Install Fan

Install Fan from stock Hot End unto the Fan Shroud using 4ea 4-20 Steel Rolling Thread Screws for Plastic 1" in length.

Plug the Heater, Thermistor, and Fan cable connectors into the Circuit Board. Secure the wiring using a Cable Tie Wrap to a binding eyelet on the Adapter Base.

Note the Fan is the top connector.

Mount Adapter unto Carriage

Mount the Adapter Assembly unto the Carriage using 2 M3x6 Screws (top) and 2 M3x12 Screws (bottom). The top screw length may need to be adjusted based on the Test Fit step above.

Connect the Processor Board to Hot End cable and secure cable cover to an eyelet on the Adapter. Best results has the cable routed to the left and secured to the PTFE tub at halfway between the aft of the printer and the new Hot End Adapter:

Harness Routing Cable Chain Installation Adjust Bed Height

Load Filament using the normal Loading procedure from the front panel.

Once the filament has loaded, clean the Nozzle with a brass brush. Select Z-Axis adjustment off the Utilities Menu. Allow the Bed to rise to the top position and the Carriage to move the Hot End to the front right printer position. Manually position the Nozzle to the middle front of the Bed. It may be necessary to lower the Bed slightly using the front panel Z-Axis adjustment. Position Bed to within 0.4mm (Business Card thickness) of the Nozzle. The card should move freely between the Bed and the Nozzle (tip) with a slight rub. Manually level the Bed using the thumb screws at the front and sides of the bed using a business card as a gauge.

Note: Recheck Front, Right, & Left adjustments after any movement of the leveling screws. Often a movement of one leveling screw affects the clearance of all three points.

Test Printer and New Hot End

Print a small object such as a calibration cube. Some adjustment may needed to the Extruder temperature.

Note: The E3DV6 Hot End causes the printer to increase the Extruder temperature 10°C over the setting specified in the XYZware for unknown reasons. Perhaps the smaller heat block and more efficient heat break is not bleeding energy at the same rate as the stock hot end and thereby confusing the firmware... but that is only a guess. To compensate subtract 10 degrees from the setting normally used for a particular filament.

This anomaly has the added benefit of supporting filaments (such as PETG) that require 250 degree temperatures.

Teach students how to use ultra-sonic sensors to program a simple obstacle avoidance robot!
Lessons and a sample code are attached in the thing files. Scroll Down for the activity information.

When my daughter was three she wanted a baby sibling for SCRU-FE (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:780050). I said Challenge accepted! and looked through my small robotics parts to make an even smaller and simpler baby robot.

Use it for Fun, Programming Practice, or to connect additional sensors for a turtle bot swarm to gather information!

This robot uses 9g size continuous rotation servos to simplify design and coding, a #952 Ball caster from Pololu and the treads from #1127 Solarbotics wheels which fit over the round servo horn and have great traction.

It allows students to focus more on sensors rather that trying to figure out motor controller boards and is an awesome first robot to build.

I am hoping to use this robot with my students in the future as the first robotics lesson in High School Robotics, and for Middle School as the introduction to advanced robotics after my beginner robotics lessons (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1696610). A few days worth of programming lessons are included in the thing files.

Assembly Instructions and Tips

  • Attach the US Sensor mount to the body with a 6mm long M3 capscrew from each side. The size of the print allows the M3 screw to thread into the plastic to allow the angle of the sensor to be adjusted. If this doesn't seem to thread in you can drill out the holes with a 3mm or 1/8" drill bit and use a 15mm long M3 cap screw and locking nut to secure it instead. The sensor mount should be angled slightly downward. Attach the Ultra Sonic HC-SR04 Sensor with magnet wire at the four corners or as I like to with small rubber bands (the rubber bands will help keep the sensor from breaking from handling or a fall, but will have to be replaced regularly)

  • Attach the #952 ball caster with no spacers. First clear out the holes with a 1.5mm drill bit (or 1/16" ). Then allow the M2 bolts for the caster to thread themselves into the plastic. If needed add M2 nuts in the nut keepers if your hole size it too large to lock the casters without them.

  • Drill out the servo mount holes with a 1/16" or 1.5mm drill bit. Attach the continuous rotation servos being careful not to pinch the wires as you put them in, and direct the wires through the slots toward the front. Secure them with M2 x 10mm socket cap screws and washers (if you don't have them use four included shoulder screws). Attach the round servo horns with the two smaller headed screws and slip the treads from the solarbotics #1127 tires over them, they should be a secure fit.

  • Using Thick double sided tape, thick quick drying glue or hot glue: attach the battery box in a position where the switch will be down and out of the way (behind the head is found to be best).

description.text:
Overview:

In this lesson you will be able to learn how to program using Arduino Boards in order to get a robot to sense objects and move around to avoid them autonomously.

Objectives:

Students will be able to create their first custom robot and create programs that will allow the robot to maneuver autonomously.

Students will be able to understand the importance of syntax and order in a programming language.

Students will be able to use a computer to control external devices through coding.

Audience:

This Lesson is advanced robotics for Middle School (grades 6-8) and Foundation of Robotics Unit 2 for High School Robotics (grades 9-12).

Subjects:

Math, Science, Behavioral Science, Robotics, Linguistics, Technology

Standards:

NYS MST Technology Standard 5.3: use a computer system to monitor and control external
events and/or systems.

Activity:

See Handouts located in thing files in order:

*Build your Bot! (3-4 40 minute time blocks)

*Move Your Motors! (two 40 minute time blocks)

*Sense, Think and Move! (two 40 minute time blocks)

*Get Logical! (two 40 minute time blocks)

Duration:

The Lessons I have designed do not include the robot build which would require 3-4 40 minute periods or two 80 minute periods.

In this unit there are three lessons that will each cover a 40 minute time block. It is also recommended to review one day after each lesson and allow for student time to complete the three assignments, or try out some code variations that they may come up with. The total unit should include 5-6 40 minute blocks of time, or three 80 minute blocks of time.

Preparation:

In order to make this unit succesful you will need a computer, USB cable and the correct download of Arduino IDE that will communicate with the boards you are using. You will also need an assembled robot for each group, or extra time for robot assembly.

Unfortunately during my different unmounts & remount I’ve quite broken the i3-08 component, the acrylic part, the Z top mount.
I’ve wrote to my GEEETech contact and I’ve immediately receive the STL file to reprint this component and I’ve do… but when I’ve mount it I start to think: with my customization I’ve loose 10mm in Z, why do not design something to recover this loose?

With this Spool Holder you can update your Z up to 20mm, in my case I’ve just recover the -10 and add 5 more, so now my Z are able to go up to 185mm!
Here you can find both right side and left side Spool Holder, in order to accommodate the i3C dual extruder!
You can also find three component to better drive the spool, the 0R/L/D!

With this stopper you can prevent your window to be close by itself. The stopper isn´t a solid block, so when you accidently close the windows, the stopper will break but it will not take the window off its hinge.

I will make a stopper for the other side too. And i have to adjust the dimensions a little bit.
